stylometry: Aggregate planning attempts to match supply and demand by determining the appropriate amount and timing of inputs, transportation, and outputs. Decisions made on production, staffing, inventory, and backorder levels are base dupon aggregate planning. Examples would be the minimum workforce level, or the maximum customer service. The trade-offs involved in aggregate planning are the costs associated with different decisons. For example, pay to store inventory to meet demand (produce ahead of time) or make inventory as orders come in? These decisons can cause delays or if you make inventory ahead of time wou can run out of your supply. If you make inventory ahead of time, you can also risk having left-overs and paying extra for storage. Aggregate planning helps determine your best options.
